# go-pdf-to-wav

Converts a PDF file to a WAV audio file using [Piper TTS](https://github.com/rhasspy/piper).

Text is extracted from the PDF, split into chunks, and converted to speech in parallel. The resulting WAV chunks are then merged into a single output file.

## Installation

```bash
git clone https://github.com/ZakariaAboudia/go-pdf-to-wav.git
cd go-pdf-to-wav
sudo docker compose up --build
docker exec -it go-pdf-to-wav-golang-app-1 bash
```

Inside the container, download Piper and a voice model:

```bash
chmod +x get-piper.sh && ./get-piper.sh
mkdir -p piper/voices
wget -O piper/voices/en_US-libritts_r-medium.onnx \
  https://huggingface.co/rhasspy/piper-voices/resolve/main/en/en_US/libritts_r/medium/en_US-libritts_r-medium.onnx
```

Build and run:

```bash
go build -o app .
./app --filepath /path/to/document.pdf
```

## Usage

```
./app [options]

Options:
  --filepath   path to the input PDF file (required)
  --voice      path to the Piper .onnx voice model
               (default: ./piper/voices/en_US-libritts_r-medium.onnx)
  --workers    number of parallel Piper processes
               (default: half the number of CPU cores)
```

## Example

```bash
./app --filepath book.pdf --workers 2
```

Produces `book.wav` in the current directory.
